          "id": "digital-marketing-101-l02-c2",
          "title": "On-Page SEO Elements",
          "content": "On-page SEO is all about making specific changes directly on your website to help it show up better in search engines like Google. One of the key components of on-page SEO is the title tag. This is the title that appears in search results and also in the tabs of your web browser. It’s important to include your main keyword in this title and keep it under 60 characters so that it’s clear and concise.\nAnother important element is the meta description. This is the short summary that appears right below the title in search results. You want this to be catchy and informative, ideally between 150 and 160 characters long. A good meta description encourages people to click on your link when they see it in the search results. Think of it as a mini-advertisement for your page!\nWhen structuring your content, you should use a single H1 tag for the main title of your page. This helps search engines understand what your page is about. For subheadings, use H2 and H3 tags. This creates a clear structure for your content, making it easier for readers to follow along.\nIt’s also a good practice to include your target keyword naturally within the first 100 words of your content. This helps search engines identify the main topic of your page right away. Additionally, make sure to include your keyword in at least one subheading and in the URL of the page.\nLastly, don’t forget about images! Using alt text for your images is crucial. Alt text describes what the image is about and can include relevant keywords. This not only improves accessibility for people who may have visual impairments but also helps your images rank better in search results. By optimizing these on-page elements, you can significantly enhance your website's visibility and user experience.\nContext recap: On-page SEO is all about making specific changes directly on your website to help it show up better in search engines like Google. One of the key components of on-page SEO is the title tag. This is the title that appears in search results and also in the tabs of your web browser. It’s important to include your main keyword in this title and keep it under 60 characters so that it’s clear and concise.\nWhy this matters: On-Page SEO Elements helps learners in Digital Marketing connect ideas from Digital Marketing Fundamentals to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
